title: For Sale:  Remington 788 + Ammo+ Case
postcontent:
Remington Model 788      Caliber .222 Remington     Early 1970's  
Weaver K4 C3    4 X 38 Scope   Fine Cross Hairs     Blued Steel Tube  + Mounts
3 & 1/2 Boxes  (71 Rds.)  .222 Rem 50 Grain SP
Rifle Case                   $620.00  OBO

The Remington 788 is an accurate hunting rifle developed by the Remington Arms Company.

 The 788 utilizes a single-column detachable magazine holding 4 rounds. A .22 rimfire model was also produced known as the 580, 581, or 582 depending on its method of feed.

 A target version  was used by the US military[2] as a training rifle and later disposed through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.

Distinguishing design characteristics
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles.
The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs. The locking bolt requires the safety to be in the "fire" or "off" position in order to rotate the handle and actuate the bolt. Rifles manufactured from 1975 to 1983 have non-locking bolts which can be actuated while the safety is engaged.
The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well.
When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength.
These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter.
A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.

Feel free to call if interested RJ Barber REDACTED

title: For Sale:  REMINGTON 1903-A3  30-06    **FRESH OUT OF THE COSMOLINE**
postcontent:
Remington 1903-A3

This is the nicest 03-A3 you will find and I will tell you why.

I found this Remington in a box that it had been sealed in since 1955.

When I opened the box 4 years ago, the rifle was covered in Cosmoline soaked bandages.  After thoroughly cleaning the rifle, it was apparent that this wasn't your average A3.  The condition is beautiful, from the warm glow of the stock to the almost flawless finish on the action & barrel.  The proof marks and serial number are deep and clear.

The proof marks tell the history:  The parts were made in April of 1943, the rifle was built in August of 1943 by Remington, final inspection was done by Lt. Col. Frank Atwood.  The rifle was at some point shipped to the Rock Island Arsenal where it was inspected and stored by Frank Krack.  Current condition would be "Unissued after rebuild".

More pictures available upon request.

I test fired the rifle at 600 yards (yes, 600!) and it grouped around 12". 

A beautiful example of a 70 year old rifle, it probably belongs in a museum.

Call, text or email Scott at 843 - 297 - 274 ZERO

title: For Sale:  Remington 788 + Ammo+ Case
postcontent:
Remington Model 788 Caliber .222 Remington Early 1970's
Weaver K4 C3 4 X 38 Scope Fine Cross Hairs Blued Steel Tube + Mounts
3 & 1/2 Boxes (71 Rds.) .222 Rem 50 Grain SP
Rifle Case $620.00 OBO

The Remington 788 is an accurate hunting rifle developed by the Remington Arms Company.

The 788 utilizes a single-column detachable magazine holding 4 rounds. A .22 rimfire model was also produced known as the 580, 581, or 582 depending on its method of feed.

A target version was used by the US military[2] as a training rifle and later disposed through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.

Distinguishing design characteristics
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles.
The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs. The locking bolt requires the safety to be in the "fire" or "off" position in order to rotate the handle and actuate the bolt. Rifles manufactured from 1975 to 1983 have non-locking bolts which can be actuated while the safety is engaged.
The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well.
When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength.
These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter.
A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.

Feel free to call if interested RJ Barber REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Not Your Typical SKS
postcontent: This is a Yugoslavian SKS. All matching numbers gun. I removed the stock and meticulously hand sanded every blemish out of the beautiful Baltic Birch. Then I applied 15 coats of Tung Oil Gloss Finish. (one coat per day for 15 days) Between each coat, I buffed the entire stock with 0000 steel wool to get a beautiful resulting high gloss and durable finish. This is the kind of Finish put on very high dollar rifles. You will not find a more beautiful SKS, anywhere. The firing pin was replaced with a Murray's stainless steel firing pin and spring set. The gas valve was replaced with a Murray's stainless steel gas valve. The original parts that were replaced come with the rifle upon sale. I sent the trigger assembly to Bill Springfield , (http://www.triggerwork.net/sksrifles.html) and he did a great trigger job, reducing the length of pull and removing all grittiness in the trigger. Also he reduced the trigger pull from over 8lbs. to just a hair over 4lbs. Needless to say, this SKS shoots like a dream. By far the smoothest, most accurate SKS I have shot in 40 years of shooting. Included  are : a Tapco 20 rd. magazine,  one dust cover scope mount with a no-name 4x scope, and another dust cover scope mount with a BSA Red Dot scope. Personally, I prefer the stock sights, but to each their own.  You wont find a prettier, smoother shooting , or more accurate SKS. The bore shows very little wear and the accuracy proves it. Comes with original web sling and original magazine. This is the model with grenade launcher , grenade sights and phosphorescent night sights, original blade bayonet, and correct cleaning kit (in the buttstock) and cleaning rod.  I know I am asking  a premium price, but when you see this rifle in person, it is a gem.  Will consider trading this and a S&W M&P 15-22 ( my other listing) for a good AR-15 w/ fwd. assist, not a "sport".

title: For Sale:  Enfield No 1 Mk III - 1944, all matching
postcontent:
.303 British Enfield made during WWII at Ishapore when it was still under British control.  These early Ishapores are difficult to find at all, much less in this condition and with all matching numbers.  All original, matching serial numbers (receiver, barrel, bolt, rear sight, nosecap).  Buttstock is correctly marked and dated for the gun with sharp original markings.  Very good condition and is a pre-1968 import.  Just has British export markings on it and "England" on the receiver.  Retains much arsenal metal finish.  Stock set is solid with some assorted dings.  Has one hairline crack about 2" long on the right side of the forestock.  It isn't structural and I have shot it with no problems - I never bothered to fix it, but it would be an easy glue job.  See the pic.  I took the picture with the lighting angled to intentionally make the crack show, so it looks worse in the pic than in hand.  

Very good bore with very strong rifling, good shine, and just a bit of scattered light pitting in a few places.  The gun is a good shooter.  When I bought it, it was missing the magazine and I have shot it single shot, but it isn't all that hard to find a magazine on-line or at a gun show.  I just never got around to it.  I am selling it as I bought it and pricing it to sell, even accounting for the missing magazine.  

The only trades I might be interested in would be USGI M14 parts or possibly 300 rounds of quality surplus 7.62 NATO ammo (Portugese, South African, etc.)

Or $175 cash firm face to face in Hickory, NC.
